CAPE TOWN- The Allan Gray Orbis Foundation is offering young students an opportunity to develop into South Africa’s future high-impact entrepreneurs through it’s 2023 Fellowship Programme. The fellowship opportunity is intended for all entrepreneurially-minded Grade 12 pupils across the country. Fellowship recipients, known as Candidate Allan Gray Fellows, receive access to entrepreneurial mindset development interventions, funding for university studies as well as personal and academic development support. In a statement on Monday, the foundation said: “The fellowship is one of four distinct programmes that the foundation offers in pursuit of creating a pipeline of high-impact responsible entrepreneurs. The fellowship gives students a stepping-stone to nurture their entrepreneurial potential and to grow into well-rounded, high-impact responsible entrepreneurs.” Applications for the scholarship opened last week, and are set to close on April 29 this year. Applicants with a combined annual household income of R1 million and below will receive full funding. Applicants with a combined household income above R1m will receive needs-based funding. Application requirements include: South African citizenship; 21 years of age or younger in 2022; Indications of an entrepreneurial mindset; Minimum of 60% in Mathematics, or a minimum of 80% in Mathematical Literacy, for final Grade 11 results; Minimum average of 70% for final Grade 11 results (excluding Life Orientation); Intention to study towards a commerce, science (excluding medicine, veterinary science and dentistry); engineering, law, humanities or arts degree at the University of the Witwatersrand, University of Johannesburg, University of Cape Town, Nelson Mandela University, Rhodes University, University of the Western Cape, Stellenbosch University, University of Pretoria, University of the Free State or University of KwaZulu-Natal Visit www.allangrayorbis.org to download an application form, or to apply online.  Cape Times